LEAD = """<strong>A gold refinery receives unrefined feed &mdash; mine dor&eacute;, recycled jewellery and industrial scrap &mdash; assays every lot to establish its exact precious metal content, refines the metal to investment-grade purity (995.0 to 999.9 fineness), casts it into certified bars, and settles with each supplier based on the assayed content of their delivery.</strong> Refineries are the quality gate of the world gold market: their accreditation, assay integrity and sourcing controls determine which metal can enter the legitimate market at all."""

BODY = """
<h2>The Refinery's Workflow</h2>
<ol>
<li><strong>Receiving.</strong> Incoming lots arrive under chain-of-custody seals, are checked against documents and weighed on calibrated scales &mdash; the supplier or their representative may witness.</li>
<li><strong>Melt and assay.</strong> Each lot is melted to homogeneity and sampled, with purity established by fire assay and supporting instrumental methods &mdash; the process described in <a href="/knowledge/how-does-a-gold-refinery-assay-work/">How Does a Gold Refinery Assay Work?</a> The assay determines what the supplier is paid.</li>
<li><strong>Refining.</strong> The metal is purified in stages (see below) to the target fineness.</li>
<li><strong>Casting and certification.</strong> Refined gold is cast into bars &mdash; kilobars, Good Delivery bars, minted products &mdash; stamped with the refinery's mark, fineness, weight and serial number, and recorded on bar lists.</li>
<li><strong>Settlement.</strong> Suppliers are paid on assayed fine content per their agreements &mdash; see <a href="/knowledge/gold-refinery-settlement-process/">the settlement process</a> in detail.</li>
</ol>

<h2>The Refining Processes</h2>
<h3>Miller process (chlorination)</h3>
<p>Chlorine gas is bubbled through molten metal; base metals and silver form chlorides that separate from the gold. The Miller process is fast and economical, taking gold to roughly 99.5% purity &mdash; sufficient for 995.0 Good Delivery feedstock but short of 999.9.</p>
<h3>Wohlwill process (electrolysis)</h3>
<p>Miller-refined gold is cast into anodes and electrolytically dissolved and redeposited as ultra-pure gold at the cathode, achieving 999.9 fineness. Slower and more capital-intensive, it produces the four-nines gold required for kilobars and high-specification uses.</p>
<h3>Aqua regia and solvent routes</h3>
<p>Chemical dissolution and selective precipitation routes are used by many refineries, particularly for complex feeds and for recovering by-metals such as silver and platinum-group metals, which are credited or returned under the supplier agreement.</p>

<h2>Accreditation: Why It Matters Commercially</h2>
<p>The market distinguishes sharply between accredited and non-accredited refineries. <a href="/knowledge/what-is-lbma-pricing/">LBMA Good Delivery</a> accreditation &mdash; and hub equivalents such as DMCC accreditation in Dubai &mdash; certify a refinery's assaying competence, bar quality and responsible sourcing controls, with ongoing audits. Bars from accredited refineries trade globally on the strength of their stamp; bars from unknown refineries face re-assay and discounts. For a seller, delivering to an accredited refinery means the assay will be credible, the settlement bankable and the output marketable.</p>

<h2>Sourcing Controls: The Refinery as Gatekeeper</h2>
<p>Because refining is where untraceable feed becomes standardised bars, refineries carry the heaviest due diligence duties in the supply chain &mdash; OECD-aligned programmes, supplier KYC, origin verification and annual independent audits (see <a href="/knowledge/oecd-gold-supply-chain-guidance/">OECD Gold Supply Chain Guidance</a>). A refinery accepts reputational and regulatory liability with every lot; this is why new suppliers face searching onboarding, and why metal without provable origin finds no reputable refinery willing to touch it.</p>

<h2>Example</h2>
<p>A 30 kg dor&eacute; lot arrives in Dubai at an accredited refinery. Day 1: receipt, weighing, melt, sampling. Day 3: fire assay confirms 90.1% gold, 7.2% silver. The supplier is settled on 27.03 kg fine gold at the contractual benchmark price less charges, with a silver credit per the agreement. The metal joins the refining stream &mdash; Miller chlorination, then Wohlwill electrolysis &mdash; and within days exists as 999.9 kilobars bearing the refinery's stamp, sold into regional demand. The supplier's dor&eacute; has become bankable, market-grade gold.</p>
"""

